#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:716
#, no-c-format
msgid "Editing the Reverse Zone"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:717
#, no-c-format
msgid "After adding a forward zone, go back to the main menu and select the reverse zone for editing. There in the tab <guimenu>Basics</guimenu> activate the check box <guimenu>Automatically Generate Records From</guimenu> and select your forward zone. That way, all changes to the forward zone are automatically updated in the reverse zone."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:730
#, no-c-format
msgid "Starting the BIND Name Server"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:732
#, no-c-format
msgid "On a &productnamereg; system, the name server BIND ( <emphasis>Berkeley Internet Name Domain</emphasis> ) comes preconfigured, so it can be started right after installation without any problems. Normally, if you already have an Internet connection and entered <systemitem class=\"ipaddress\">127.0.0.1</systemitem> as the name server address for <systemitem class=\"domainname\">localhost</systemitem> in <filename>/var/run/netconfig/resolv.conf</filename> , you already have a working name resolution without needing to know the DNS of the provider. BIND carries out name resolution via the root name server, a notably slower process. Normally, the DNS of the provider should be entered with its IP address in the configuration file <filename>/etc/named.conf</filename> under <systemitem>forwarders</systemitem> to ensure effective and secure name resolution. If this works so far, the name server runs as a pure <emphasis>caching-only</emphasis> name server. Only when you configure its own zones it becomes a proper DNS. Find a simple example documented in <filename>/usr/share/doc/packages/bind/config</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:751
#, no-c-format
msgid "Automatic Adaptation of the Name Server Information"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:752
#, no-c-format
msgid "Depending on the type of Internet connection or the network connection, the name server information can automatically be adapted to the current conditions. To do this, set the <systemitem>NETCONFIG_DNS_POLICY</systemitem> variable in the <filename>/etc/sysconfig/network/config</filename> file to <literal>auto</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:762
#, no-c-format
msgid "However, do not set up an official domain until one is assigned to you by the responsible institution. Even if you have your own domain and it is managed by the provider, you are better off not using it, because BIND would otherwise not forward requests for this domain. The Web server at the provider, for example, would not be accessible for this domain."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:770
#, no-c-format
msgid "To start the name server, enter the command <command>systemctl start named</command> as <systemitem class=\"username\">root</systemitem> . Check with <command>systemctl status named</command> whether named (as the name server process is called) has been started successfully. Test the name server immediately on the local system with the <command>host</command> or <command>dig</command> programs, which should return <systemitem class=\"domainname\">localhost</systemitem> as the default server with the address <systemitem class=\"ipaddress\">127.0.0.1</systemitem> . If this is not the case, <filename>/var/run/netconfig/resolv.conf</filename> probably contains an incorrect name server entry or the file does not exist. For the first test, enter <command>host</command> &nbsp; <option>127.0.0.1</option> , which should always work. If you get an error message, use <command>systemctl status named</command> to see whether the server is actually running. If the name server does not start or behaves unexpectedly, check the output of <command>journalctl -e</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:790
#, no-c-format
msgid "To use the name server of the provider (or one already running on your network) as the forwarder, enter the corresponding IP address or addresses in the <systemitem>options</systemitem> section under <systemitem>forwarders</systemitem> . The addresses included in <xref linkend=\"ex-forward\"/> are examples only. Adjust these entries to your own setup."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:800
#, no-c-format
msgid "Forwarding Options in named.conf"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:804
#, no-c-format
msgid "options {\n"
      "        directory \"/var/lib/named\";\n"
      "        forwarders { 10.11.12.13; 10.11.12.14; };\n"
      "        listen-on { 127.0.0.1; &dnsip;; };\n"
      "        allow-query { 127/8; 192.168/16 };\n"
      "        notify no;\n"
      "};"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:813
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <systemitem>options</systemitem> entry is followed by entries for the zone, <systemitem class=\"domainname\">localhost</systemitem> , and <systemitem>0.0.127.in-addr.arpa</systemitem> . The <literal>type hint</literal> entry under <quote>.</quote> should always be present. The corresponding files do not need to be modified and should work as they are. Also make sure that each entry is closed with a <quote>;</quote> and that the curly braces are in the correct places. After changing the configuration file <filename>/etc/named.conf</filename> or the zone files, tell BIND to reread them with <command>systemctl reload named</command> . Achieve the same by stopping and restarting the name server with <command>systemctl restart named</command> . Stop the server at any time by entering <command>systemctl stop named</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:829
#, no-c-format
msgid "The /etc/named.conf Configuration File"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:831
#, no-c-format
msgid "All the settings for the BIND name server itself are stored in the <filename>/etc/named.conf</filename> file. However, the zone data for the domains to handle (consisting of the host names, IP addresses, and so on) are stored in separate files in the <filename>/var/lib/named</filename> directory. The details of this are described later."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:839
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>/etc/named.conf</filename> is roughly divided into two areas. One is the <systemitem>options</systemitem> section for general settings and the other consists of <systemitem>zone</systemitem> entries for the individual domains. A <systemitem>logging</systemitem> section and <systemitem>acl</systemitem> (access control list) entries are optional. Comment lines begin with a <literal>#</literal> sign or <literal>//</literal> . A minimal <filename>/etc/named.conf</filename> is shown in <xref linkend=\"ex-named-mini\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:851
#, no-c-format
msgid "A Basic /etc/named.conf"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:852
#, no-c-format
msgid "options {\n"
      "        directory \"/var/lib/named\";\n"
      "        forwarders { 10.0.0.1; };\n"
      "        notify no;\n"
      "};\n"
      "\n"
      "zone \"localhost\" in {\n"
      "       type master;\n"
      "       file \"localhost.zone\";\n"
      "};\n"
      "\n"
      "zone \"0.0.127.in-addr.arpa\" in {\n"
      "        type master;\n"
      "        file \"127.0.0.zone\";\n"
      "};\n"
      "\n"
      "zone \".\" in {\n"
      "        type hint;\n"
      "        file \"root.hint\";\n"
      "};"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:875
#, no-c-format
msgid "Important Configuration Options"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:878
#, no-c-format
msgid "directory \" <replaceable>FILENAME</replaceable> \";"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:880
#, no-c-format
msgid "Specifies the directory in which BIND can find the files containing the zone data. Usually, this is <filename>/var/lib/named</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:887
#, no-c-format
msgid "forwarders { <replaceable>IP-ADDRESS</replaceable> ; };"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:889
#, no-c-format
msgid "Specifies the name servers (mostly of the provider) to which DNS requests should be forwarded if they cannot be resolved directly. Replace <replaceable>IP-ADDRESS</replaceable> with an IP address like <literal>&dnsip;</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:898
#, no-c-format
msgid "forward first;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:900
#, no-c-format
msgid "Causes DNS requests to be forwarded before an attempt is made to resolve them via the root name servers. Instead of <systemitem>forward first</systemitem> , <systemitem>forward only</systemitem> can be written to have all requests forwarded and none sent to the root name servers. This makes sense for firewall configurations."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:910
#, no-c-format
msgid "listen-on port 53 { 127.0.0.1; <replaceable>IP-ADDRESS</replaceable> ; };"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:912
#, no-c-format
msgid "Tells BIND on which network interfaces and port to accept client queries. <literal>port 53</literal> does not need to be specified explicitly, because <literal>53</literal> is the default port. Enter <literal>127.0.0.1</literal> to permit requests from the local host. If you omit this entry entirely, all interfaces are used by default."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:922
#, no-c-format
msgid "listen-on-v6 port 53 {any; };"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:924
#, no-c-format
msgid "Tells BIND on which port it should listen for IPv6 client requests. The only alternative to <literal>any</literal> is <literal>none</literal> . As far as IPv6 is concerned, the server only accepts wild card addresses."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:933
#, no-c-format
msgid "query-source address * port 53;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:935
#, no-c-format
msgid "This entry is necessary if a firewall is blocking outgoing DNS requests. This tells BIND to post requests externally from port 53 and not from any of the high ports above 1024."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:943
#, no-c-format
msgid "query-source-v6 address * port 53;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:945
#, no-c-format
msgid "Tells BIND which port to use for IPv6 queries."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:951
#, no-c-format
msgid "allow-query { 127.0.0.1; <replaceable>NET</replaceable> ; };"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:953
#, no-c-format
msgid "Defines the networks from which clients can post DNS requests. Replace <replaceable>NET</replaceable> with address information like <literal>&subnetIImask;</literal> . The <systemitem>/24</systemitem> at the end is an abbreviated expression for the netmask (in this case <systemitem class=\"netmask\">255.255.255.0</systemitem> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:963
#, no-c-format
msgid "allow-transfer ! *;;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:965
#, no-c-format
msgid "Controls which hosts can request zone transfers. In the example, such requests are completely denied with <systemitem>! *</systemitem> . Without this entry, zone transfers can be requested from anywhere without restrictions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:974
#, no-c-format
msgid "statistics-interval 0;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:976
#, no-c-format
msgid "In the absence of this entry, BIND generates several lines of statistical information per hour in the system's journal. Set it to 0 to suppress these statistics completely or set an interval in minutes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:984
#, no-c-format
msgid "cleaning-interval 720;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:986
#, no-c-format
msgid "This option defines at which time intervals BIND clears its cache. This triggers an entry in the system's journal each time it occurs. The time specification is in minutes. The default is 60 minutes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:994
#, no-c-format
msgid "interface-interval 0;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:996
#, no-c-format
msgid "BIND regularly searches the network interfaces for new or nonexistent interfaces. If this value is set to <systemitem>0</systemitem> , this is not done and BIND only listens at the interfaces detected at start-up. Otherwise, the interval can be defined in minutes. The default is sixty minutes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:1006
#, no-c-format
msgid "notify no;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1008
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>no</option> prevents other name servers from being informed when changes are made to the zone data or when the name server is restarted."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1015
#, no-c-format
msgid "For a list of available options, read the manual page <command>man 5 named.conf</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1022
#, no-c-format
msgid "Logging"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1023
#, no-c-format
msgid "What, how, and where logging takes place can be extensively configured in BIND. Normally, the default settings should be sufficient. <xref linkend=\"ex-no-log\"/> , shows the simplest form of such an entry and completely suppresses any logging."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1030
#, no-c-format
msgid "Entry to Disable Logging"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:1031
#, no-c-format
msgid "logging {\n"
      "        category default { null; };\n"
      "};"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1038
#, no-c-format
msgid "Zone Entries"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1040
#, no-c-format
msgid "Zone Entry for example.com"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:1041
#, no-c-format
msgid "zone \"example.com\" in {\n"
      "      type master;\n"
      "      file \"example.com.zone\";\n"
      "      notify no;\n"
      "};"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1047
#, no-c-format
msgid "After <systemitem>zone</systemitem> , specify the name of the domain to administer ( <systemitem class=\"domainname\">example.com</systemitem> ) followed by <systemitem>in</systemitem> and a block of relevant options enclosed in curly braces, as shown in <xref linkend=\"ex-meine-domain\"/> . To define a <emphasis>slave zone</emphasis> , switch the <systemitem>type</systemitem> to <literal>slave</literal> and specify a name server that administers this zone as <literal>master</literal> (which, in turn, may be a slave of another master), as shown in <xref linkend=\"ex-andere-domain\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1059
#, no-c-format
msgid "Zone Entry for &exampledomain1;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:1060
#, no-c-format
msgid "zone \"&exampledomain1;\" in {\n"
      "      type slave;\n"
      "      file \"slave/&exampledomain1;.zone\";\n"
      "      masters { 10.0.0.1; }; <!-- network scheme: What is this external DNS' IP supposed to be?\n"
      "      bg: we still did not define the addresses of a public internet.-->\n"
      "};"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1067
#, no-c-format
msgid "The zone options:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:1072
#, no-c-format
msgid "type master;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1074
#, no-c-format
msgid "By specifying <literal>master</literal> , tell BIND that the zone is handled by the local name server. This assumes that a zone file has been created in the correct format."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:1082
#, no-c-format
msgid "type slave;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1084
#, no-c-format
msgid "This zone is transferred from another name server. It must be used together with <systemitem>masters</systemitem> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:1091
#, no-c-format
msgid "type hint;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1093
#, no-c-format
msgid "The zone <literal>.</literal> of the <literal>hint</literal> type is used to set the root name servers. This zone definition can be left as is."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:1101
#, no-c-format
msgid "file <filename>&exampledomain;.zone</filename> or file <quote>slave/&exampledomain1;.zone</quote> ;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1104
#, no-c-format
msgid "This entry specifies the file where zone data for the domain is located. This file is not required for a slave, because this data is pulled from another name server. To differentiate master and slave files, use the directory <filename>slave</filename> for the slave files."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:1113
#, no-c-format
msgid "masters { <replaceable>SERVER_IP_ADDRESS</replaceable> ; };"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1115
#, no-c-format
msgid "This entry is only needed for slave zones. It specifies from which name server the zone file should be transferred."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_dns.xml:1122
#, no-c-format
msgid "allow-update {! *; };"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1124
#, no-c-format
msgid "This option controls external write access, which would allow clients to make a DNS entry&mdash;something not normally desirable for security reasons. Without this entry, zone updates are not allowed. The above entry achieves the same because <literal>! *</literal> effectively bans any such activity."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1137
#, no-c-format
msgid "Zone Files"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1139
#, no-c-format
msgid "Two types of zone files are needed. One assigns IP addresses to host names and the other does the reverse: it supplies a host name for an IP address."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1145
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using the Dot (Period, Fullstop) in Zone Files"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1146
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <literal>\".\"</literal> has an important meaning in the zone files. If host names are given without a final dot ( <literal>.</literal> ), the zone is appended. Complete host names specified with a full domain name must end with a dot ( <literal>.</literal> ) to avoid having the domain added to it again. A missing or wrongly placed \".\" is probably the most frequent cause of name server configuration errors."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1189
#, no-c-format
msgid "The first case to consider is the zone file <filename>&exampledomain;.zone</filename> , responsible for the domain <filename>&exampledomain;</filename> , shown in <xref linkend=\"ex-welt-zone\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1197
#, no-c-format
msgid "The /var/lib/named/&exampledomain;.zone File"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:1198
#, no-c-format
msgid "$TTL 2D <co xml:id=\"welt-zone-ttl\"/>\n"
      "&exampledomain;. IN SOA      dns  root.&exampledomain;. ( <co xml:id=\"welt-zone-soa-start\"/>\n"
      "             2003072441  ; serial <co xml:id=\"welt-zone-serial-no\"/>\n"
      "             1D          ; refresh <co xml:id=\"welt-zone-refresh\"/>\n"
      "             2H          ; retry <co xml:id=\"welt-zone-retry\"/>\n"
      "             1W          ; expiry <co xml:id=\"welt-zone-expire\"/>\n"
      "             2D )        ; minimum <co xml:id=\"welt-zone-caching-time\"/>\n"
      "\n"
      "             IN NS       dns <co xml:id=\"welt-zone-inns\"/>\n"
      "             IN MX       10 mail dns <co xml:id=\"welt-zone-mx\"/>\n"
      "gate         IN A        &gateip; <co xml:id=\"welt-zone-ips\"/>\n"
      "             IN A        10.0.0.1\n"
      "dns          IN A        &dnsip;\n"
      "mail         IN A        &mailip;\n"
      "&wsI;      IN A        &wsIip;\n"
      "&wsII;        IN A        &wsIIip;\n"
      "&wsIII;       IN A        &wsIIIip;\n"
      "&wsIV;      IN A        &wsIVip;\n"
      "ntp          IN CNAME    dns <co xml:id=\"welt-zone-ntp\"/>\n"
      "dns6         IN A6  0    &dnsipv6;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1230
#, no-c-format
msgid "<systemitem>$TTL</systemitem> defines the default time to live that should apply to all the entries in this file. In this example, entries are valid for a period of two days ( <literal>2 D</literal> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1237
#, no-c-format
msgid "This is where the SOA (start of authority) control record begins:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1242
#, no-c-format
msgid "The name of the domain to administer is <literal>&exampledomain;</literal> in the first position. This ends with <literal>\".\"</literal> , because otherwise the zone would be appended a second time. Alternatively, <literal>@</literal> can be entered here, in which case the zone would be extracted from the corresponding entry in <filename>/etc/named.conf</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1252
#, no-c-format
msgid "After <systemitem>IN SOA</systemitem> is the name of the name server in charge as master for this zone. The name is expanded from <literal>dns</literal> to <literal>&dnsname;</literal> , because it does not end with a <literal>\".\"</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1260
#, no-c-format
msgid "An e-mail address of the person in charge of this name server follows. Because the <literal>@</literal> sign already has a special meaning, <literal>\".\"</literal> is entered here instead. For <systemitem>root@&exampledomain;</systemitem> the entry must read <systemitem>root.&exampledomain;.</systemitem> . The <literal>\".\"</literal> must be included at the end to prevent the zone from being added."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1271
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <literal>(</literal> includes all lines up to <literal>)</literal> into the SOA record."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1279
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <systemitem>serial number</systemitem> is a 10 digit number. It must be changed each time this file is changed. It is needed to inform the secondary name servers (slave servers) of changes. For this, a 10 digit number of the date and run number, written as YYYYMMDDNN, has become the customary format (YYYY = year, MM = month and DD = day. NN is a sequence number in case you update it more than once on the given day)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1289
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <systemitem>refresh rate</systemitem> specifies the time interval at which the secondary name servers verify the zone <systemitem>serial number</systemitem> . In this case, one day."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1296
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <systemitem>retry rate</systemitem> specifies the time interval at which a secondary name server, in case of error, attempts to contact the primary server again. Here, two hours."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1303
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <systemitem>expiration time</systemitem> specifies the time frame after which a secondary name server discards the cached data if it has not regained contact to the primary server. Here, a week."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1310
#, no-c-format
msgid "The last entry in the SOA record specifies the <systemitem>negative caching TTL</systemitem> &mdash;the time for which results of unresolved DNS queries from other servers may be cached."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1317
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <systemitem>IN NS</systemitem> specifies the name server responsible for this domain. <systemitem>dns</systemitem> is extended to <systemitem>&dnsname;</systemitem> because it does not end with a <literal>\".\"</literal> . There can be several lines like this&mdash;one for the primary and one for each secondary name server. If <systemitem>notify</systemitem> is not set to <option>no</option> in <filename>/etc/named.conf</filename> , all the name servers listed here are informed of the changes made to the zone data."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1329
#, no-c-format
msgid "The MX record specifies the mail server that accepts, processes, and forwards e-mails for the domain <systemitem class=\"domainname\">&exampledomain;</systemitem> . In this example, this is the host <systemitem class=\"domainname\">&mailname;</systemitem> . The number in front of the host name is the preference value. If there are multiple MX entries, the mail server with the smallest value is taken first. If mail delivery to this server fails, the entry with the next-smallest value is used."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1341
#, no-c-format
msgid "This and the following lines are the actual address records where one or more IP addresses are assigned to host names. The names are listed here without a <literal>\".\"</literal> because they do not include their domain, so <systemitem class=\"domainname\">&exampledomain;</systemitem> is added to all of them. Two IP addresses are assigned to the host <systemitem>gate</systemitem> , as it has two network cards. <!-- looks as if we don't support A6 at least with YAST --> Wherever the host address is a traditional one (IPv4), the record is marked with <literal>A</literal> . If the address is an IPv6 address, the entry is marked with <literal>AAAA</literal> . <!-- The previous token for IPv6 addresses was only <literal>AAAA</literal>, which is now obsolete. -->"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1359
#, no-c-format
msgid "IPv6 Syntax"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1360
#, no-c-format
msgid "The IPv6 record has a slightly different syntax than IPv4. Because of the fragmentation possibility, it is necessary to provide information about missed bits before the address. To fill up the IPv6 address with the needed number of <quote>0</quote> , add two colons at the correct place in the address. <!-- You must provide this information even if you want to use a completely unfragmented address. For the AAAA record with the syntax -->"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:1370
#, no-c-format
msgid "pluto     AAAA 2345:00C1:CA11::1234:5678:9ABC:DEF0\n"
      "pluto     AAAA 2345:00D2:DA11::1234:5678:9ABC:DEF0"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1382
#, no-c-format
msgid "The alias <literal>ntp</literal> can be used to address <literal>dns</literal> ( <systemitem>CNAME</systemitem> means <emphasis>canonical name</emphasis> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1392
#, no-c-format
msgid "The pseudo domain <literal>in-addr.arpa</literal> is used for the reverse lookup of IP addresses into host names. It is appended to the network part of the address in reverse notation. So <systemitem class=\"ipaddress\">192.168</systemitem> is resolved into <systemitem>168.192.in-addr.arpa</systemitem> . See <xref linkend=\"dat-arpa\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1404
#, no-c-format
msgid "Reverse Lookup"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:1405
#, no-c-format
msgid "$TTL 2D <co xml:id=\"data-arpa-ttl\"/>\n"
      "168.192.in-addr.arpa.   IN SOA &dnsname;. root.&exampledomain;. ( <co xml:id=\"data-arpa-soa\"/>\n"
      "                        2003072441      ; serial\n"
      "                        1D              ; refresh\n"
      "                        2H              ; retry\n"
      "                        1W              ; expiry\n"
      "                        2D )            ; minimum\n"
      "\n"
      "                        IN NS           &dnsname;. <co xml:id=\"data-arpa-inns\"/>\n"
      "\n"
      "1.5                     IN PTR          &gatename;. <co xml:id=\"data-arpa-ips\"/>\n"
      "100.3                   IN PTR          &wwwname;.\n"
      "253.2                   IN PTR          &cupsname;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1422
#, no-c-format
msgid "$TTL defines the standard TTL that applies to all entries here."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1427
#, no-c-format
msgid "The configuration file should activate reverse lookup for the network <systemitem class=\"ipaddress\">192.168</systemitem> . Given that the zone is called <systemitem>168.192.in-addr.arpa</systemitem> , it should not be added to the host names. Therefore, all host names are entered in their complete form&mdash;with their domain and with a <literal>\".\"</literal> at the end. The remaining entries correspond to those described for the previous <systemitem>&exampledomain;</systemitem> example."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1437
#, no-c-format
msgid "See <xref linkend=\"ex-welt-zone\"/> for detail on the entries within this record."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1443
#, no-c-format
msgid "This line specifies the name server responsible for this zone. This time, however, the name is entered in its complete form with the domain and a <literal>\".\"</literal> at the end."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1450
#, no-c-format
msgid "This, and the following lines, are the pointer records hinting at the IP addresses on the respective hosts. Only the last part of the IP address is entered at the beginning of the line, without the <literal>\".\"</literal> at the end. Appending the zone to this (without the <systemitem>.in-addr.arpa</systemitem> ) results in the complete IP address in reverse order."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1460
#, no-c-format
msgid "Normally, zone transfers between different versions of BIND should be possible without any problems."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1467
#, no-c-format
msgid "Dynamic Update of Zone Data"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1469
#, no-c-format
msgid "The term <emphasis>dynamic update</emphasis> refers to operations by which entries in the zone files of a master server are added, changed, or deleted. This mechanism is described in RFC&nbsp;2136. Dynamic update is configured individually for each zone entry by adding an optional <systemitem>allow-update</systemitem> or <systemitem>update-policy</systemitem> rule. Zones to update dynamically should not be edited by hand."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1479
#, no-c-format
msgid "Transmit the entries to update to the server with the command <command>nsupdate</command> . For the exact syntax of this command, check the manual page for nsupdate ( <command>man</command> &nbsp; <option>8 nsupdate</option> ). For security reasons, any such update should be performed using TSIG keys as described in <xref linkend=\"sec-dns-tsig\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1488
#, no-c-format
msgid "Secure Transactions"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1490
#, no-c-format
msgid "Secure transactions can be made with transaction signatures (TSIGs) based on shared secret keys (also called TSIG keys). This section describes how to generate and use such keys."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1496
#, no-c-format
msgid "Secure transactions are needed for communication between different servers and for the dynamic update of zone data. Making the access control dependent on keys is much more secure than merely relying on IP addresses."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1502
#, no-c-format
msgid "Generate a TSIG key with the following command (for details, see <command>man</command> &nbsp; <option>dnssec-keygen</option> ):"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:1507
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;dnssec-keygen -a hmac-md5 -b 128 -n HOST host1-host2"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1509
#, no-c-format
msgid "This creates two files with names similar to these:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:1513
#, no-c-format
msgid "Khost1-host2.+157+34265.private Khost1-host2.+157+34265.key"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1515
#, no-c-format
msgid "The key itself (a string like <literal>ejIkuCyyGJwwuN3xAteKgg==</literal> ) is found in both files. To use it for transactions, the second file ( <filename>Khost1-host2.+157+34265.key</filename> ) must be transferred to the remote host, preferably in a secure way (using scp, for example). On the remote server, the key must be included in the <filename>/etc/named.conf</filename> file to enable a secure communication between <literal>host1</literal> and <literal>host2</literal> :"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:1525
#, no-c-format
msgid "key host1-host2 {\n"
      " algorithm hmac-md5;\n"
      " secret \"ejIkuCyyGJwwuN3xAteKgg==\";\n"
      "};"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1531
#, no-c-format
msgid "File Permissions of <filename>/etc/named.conf</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1532
#, no-c-format
msgid "Make sure that the permissions of <filename>/etc/named.conf</filename> are properly restricted. The default for this file is <literal>0640</literal> , with the owner being <systemitem class=\"username\">root</systemitem> and the group <systemitem class=\"username\">named</systemitem> . As an alternative, move the keys to an extra file with specially limited permissions, which is then included from <filename>/etc/named.conf</filename> . To include an external file, use:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:1541
#, no-c-format
msgid "include  \"filename\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1542
#, no-c-format
msgid "Replace <option>filename</option> with an absolute path to your file with keys."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1548
#, no-c-format
msgid "<!--adjust to standard network example--> <!-- network schema: We have no 2xDNS setup, i used a disjoint network for --> <!-- this. Is this a problem? After all, this is just an illustration of how --> <!-- to put a key for a host, and not a beginner topic. Anyway, we'd need a --> <!-- secondary server. --> To enable the server <literal>host1</literal> to use the key for <literal>host2</literal> (which has the address <literal>10.1.2.3</literal> in this example), the server's <filename>/etc/named.conf</filename> must include the following rule:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:1560
#, no-c-format
msgid "server 10.1.2.3 {\n"
      "  keys { host1-host2. ;};\n"
      "};"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1564
#, no-c-format
msgid "Analogous entries must be included in the configuration files of <literal>host2</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1569
#, no-c-format
msgid "Add TSIG keys for any ACLs (access control lists, not to be confused with file system ACLs) that are defined for IP addresses and address ranges to enable transaction security. The corresponding entry could look like this:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_dns.xml:1575
#, no-c-format
msgid "allow-update { key host1-host2. ;};"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1577
#, no-c-format
msgid "This topic is discussed in more detail in the <emphasis>BIND Administrator Reference Manual</emphasis> under <literal>update-policy</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_dns.xml:1583
#, no-c-format
msgid "DNS Security"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1585
#, no-c-format
msgid "DNSSEC, or DNS security, is described in RFC&nbsp;2535. The tools available for DNSSEC are discussed in the BIND Manual."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1590
#, no-c-format
msgid "A zone considered secure must have one or several zone keys associated with it. These are generated with <command>dnssec-keygen</command> , as are the host keys. The DSA encryption algorithm is currently used to generate these keys. The public keys generated should be included in the corresponding zone file with an <systemitem>$INCLUDE</systemitem> rule."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_dns.xml:1598
#, no-c-format
msgid "With the command <command>dnssec-signzone</command> , you can create sets of generated keys ( <literal>keyset-</literal> files), transfer them to the parent zone in a secure manner, and sign them. This generates the files to include for each zone in <filename>/etc/named.conf</filename> ."
msgstr ""

